<dim:field qualifier="abstract" mdschema="dc" language="en_US" element="description">Watching media violence significantly increases the risk that a viewer or video game player will behave aggressively in both the short and long term, according to a University of Michigan study published today in a special issue of the Journal of Adolescent Health. The study, by L. Rowell Huesmann, reviews more than half a century of research on the impact of exposure to violence in television, movies, video games and on the Internet.&#13;
&#13;
The research clearly shows that exposure to virtual violence increases the risk that both children and adults will behave aggressively, said Huesmann, the Amos N. Tversky Collegiate Professor of Communication Studies and Psychology, and a senior research scientist at the U-M Institute for Social Research (ISR).</dim:field>
